snippet.title: House Full of Love

And they certainly never took up an entire rack on the fridge with their pizza boxes, with only one leftover slice inside, no. And they definitely didn't "accidentally" get stabbed to death in an "accidental" "accident." Wait, that sounds confusing. snippet.title: Terror on Fork Island
snippet.description: ​Their ship ran aground on the jagged reef of Bowtie Pasta Bay, a hellish oasis once thought to be a myth, meant to keep children in line. Any and all signs of solid food were forked away from their grasp as soon as they saw it. Weeks went by, subsisting only on liquids from the coconut milk streams and green tea springs, hiding in the shadows, waiting for a chance to make their escape. But there was no fooling the watchful eye of Forkon, the all-seeing, all-hungry Stab God.

snippet.title: The Death of Cinco de Mayo
snippet.description:
And lo, did the tale of Jon and Brian, two massively unstable drinking partners unbound by time and unshaken by death, come to a bitter, sobbing, wretched end. Let this be a lesson to all: Some doors were never meant to be opened, some questions never meant to be asked. If you seek the true meaning of Cinco de Mayo, you seek to stare into the gaping, terrible chasm of eternity. And foolish travelers, believe me when I say the chasm will stare back. And it will tell you.

To shut.

The fuck.

Up.

snippet.title: Crambox
snippet.description: Albert's crambox was home to many a blue feeling, sad thought and bummer memory. One could argue that a box can't hold words in speech form, and thus has no intrinsic value. But if you told that to Albert, he'd just get sad and go tell it to his crambox. It's a cycle of shame, repression and darkened closets for old Albert, and since that's all he's ever known, it's just the way he likes (and simultaneously hates) it.

snippet.title: Stoned Alone
snippet.description: ​Everyone's favorite mischievous prankster, Kevin McCallister, never left the booby-trapping game behind even as he grew into a shallow, lonely adulthood. As the cops would discover, upon getting a call from a neighbor about a weird smell from his house only to discover a rotting corpse covered in third-degree burns and house paint, it would be his undoing. They found vast amounts of THC in his body and ruled it an accidental death. But nobody bothered to notice the running water in the kitchen sink.

snippet.title: Test Notes
snippet.description:
Mrs. Blaumfgartner coughed loudly, and with a purpose. Her eyes were staring directly at the student in the back of the class. The scribbling of pencils dribbled to a stop. Soon, only the tick-tock of the second hand could be heard. Everyone knew Jimmy was in for it this time. "So, what sort of life-affirming statement have you got there this time, Jimmy?" She sniped. "Don't answer that. You'll be getting low marks for optimism, and I'll see you in after-school deflation." The rest of the class breathed in heavily and resumed their tests, making sure not to smile or nod their heads enthusiastically.

snippet.title: Roofies
snippet.description: Once his head hit the floor, she slammed her drink on the back of his skull like she was spiking a football after a touchdown. "Boom," she bellowed for all the party to hear, and then after everyone's attention was fully commanded, she pulled her hair behind her ear, adjusted her blouse, and modestly muttered "shaka-laka" as she collected her things and left. The last thing the poor boy ever heard until the paramedics woke him was the comedic scratch of the DJ's record, and to this day he can still hear it when he turns off the bedroom light. That sickening, hilarious scratch of needle on wax, followed by the silence of shame.
